someone asked this after we inflated it yesterday. So I did an underhand toss at our full metal bot and it was fine. However anything plastic might bend/snap from the weight and force. Definitely protect any exposed 3DP or be prepared to make extras.

We are planning to fully cover as much of the electronics panel as possible as well. PVC tubing falling inside of a robot chassis or the deep cage smashing a vertically mounted motor controller is a big concern I have as well

This is an interesting concern. I hadn’t though about it much before. I agree, it most likely will not pose as a big problem to metal parts on the bot but any lose plastic or even thinner metal structures that are extended (say you have a robot arm extended upwards towards the level 4 coral) could potentially be devastating. Building shielded electronics and power connection points as well as designs that will tuck any extending parts back into the safety of the chassis perimeter is the smartest way to go about decreasing risk of “large object hit bot oh no ack”.

Coral falling inside bot would be potentially more of a concern as it would block the robot from grabbing any additional coral pieces and the heavier/harder PVC may find a way to damage the robot.

I dont think that communication with the radios will be cut off by the Barge. In previous events we’ve had large obstructions in the middle of the feild (such as Crescendo with the Stage) and the radios have gotten their signal across easily : )

I like the point you brought up about the cages being a ‘wreaking ball’ issue for the robots. Those could be very distructive. I’m hoping that, since most of the robot activity is confined to the alliance’s side of the feild (with the processsor being the only thing robots would need to cross mid-line for) there won’t be too many instances of swinging cages. I suppose that would just be an issue to be talked out (making sure alliances know what team would cross the line and then how they would cross it to minimize cage swinging) by the coaches of the drive team come competition time. If the shallow cage is swinging, it shouldn’t be too much of a problem and the swinging will cease in a bit. The bigger problem is if the deep cage is hit as that would result in a swinging cage for the remainder of the match.

Question about the game rules. So I remember going through threads and wondering how the processor works. After reading the threads I interpreted it as you score into the opposing alliance’s coprocessor and you gain 6 points. After, the opposing human player has a chance to shoot and score 4.

","post_number":13,"post_type":1,"posts_count":21,"updated_at":"2025-01-28T22:49:20.690Z","reply_count":2,"reply_to_post_number":10,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":224,"readers_count":223,"score":64.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":479169,"topic_slug":"risk-of-thrown-algae","display_username":"Saahil Farook","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":55526,"username":"25MustangMech1418","name":"N Miller (Mechanic/Electrician)","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/25mustangmech1418/{size}/241230_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":67109,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/risk-of-thrown-algae/479169/13","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3495171,"name":"GaryVoshol","username":"GaryVoshol","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/garyvoshol/{size}/1658_2.png","created_at":"2025-01-28T22:52:44.011Z","cooked":"
saahilsterr:

Question

Correct. You score in the Processor in your end of the field, near your Reef. It then goes through the Processor to the opponent’s HP in the Processor Area to be thrown back into the field.

Yes, you score into the opposing alliance’s processor unit (not on your side of the feild), thereby gaining your alliance 6 points. You give the other alliance a chance to earn 4 points (if their human player can score the algae into the net). You also earn yourself the bonus in filing out the reef (fill out 5 on three of the levels instead of 4 to get the ranking point).
